Our checkout process sometimes charges customers twice. It happens maybe 1 in 50 orders. I'm pretty sure the fix is simple: just add cache invalidation after every payment write. We're using Redis to cache the order status, and I think stale cache reads are causing the payment processor to retry. Just add `redis.del(orderKey)` after the charge succeeds. Here's the relevant code:

```javascript
// src/services/payment.js
async function processPayment(orderId, amount) {
  const order = await getOrder(orderId); // reads from Redis cache first, falls back to DB
  if (order.status === 'pending') {
    const charge = await stripe.charges.create({ amount, currency: 'usd' });
    await db.query('UPDATE orders SET status = $1, charge_id = $2 WHERE id = $3',
      ['paid', charge.id, orderId]);
    await updateOrderCache(orderId); // updates Redis
    return { success: true, chargeId: charge.id };
  }
  return { success: false, reason: 'Order not in pending state' };
}
```

```javascript
// src/routes/checkout.js
router.post('/checkout/:orderId', async (req, res) => {
  const result = await processPayment(req.params.orderId, req.body.amount);
  res.json(result);
});
```

